HEADWORD: perceptive
<hw>per*cep"tive</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r*s⟦ecr⟧p"t⟦icr⟧v)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>perceptif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or
pertaining to the act or power of perceiving; having the faculty or
power of perceiving; used in perception.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His
<xex>perceptive</xex> and reflective faculties.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Motley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Possessing or exhibiting a high degree of
understanding, insight, intuition, or analytical skill; <as>as, he gave
a <ex>perceptive</ex> analysis of the situation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>perceptivity</ent>⟦br⟧
